    "mainEntity":
      - "@type": "Question"
        "name": "What did Magnifica Humanitas actually say?"
        "acceptedAnswer":
          "@type": "Answer"
          "text": "Magnifica Humanitas, Pope Leo XIV's first encyclical, released May 25, 2026, sets out the Catholic Church's framework for evaluating artificial intelligence. The encyclical argues that AI ethics is fundamentally an anthropological question about what human beings are, defends the sacredness of human faces and voices against synthetic substitutes, addresses the dignity of labor in an AI-driven economy, and calls for governance that protects the vulnerable. This page provides the morning-after analysis. For the section-by-section summary, see the Magnifica Humanitas Summary page."
      - "@type": "Question"
        "name": "What was new in Magnifica Humanitas?"
        "acceptedAnswer":
          "@type": "Answer"
          "text": "The full analysis of what was new versus expected is published on this page after the May 25 release. Going in, the most likely novel elements were specific magisterial demands that go beyond Antiqua et Nova, particularly on lethal autonomous weapons, on AI in human relationships, and on the duties of public authorities. The encyclical was also expected to advance the theological argument about why human faces and voices are sacred, building on Pope Leo XIV's prior addresses but giving the argument magisterial weight for the first time."
      - "@type": "Question"
        "name": "How is Magnifica Humanitas being received?"
        "acceptedAnswer":
          "@type": "Answer"
          "text": "Initial reception across Catholic media, secular press, AI industry, and policy commentators is documented on this page after the May 25 release. The encyclical was released at a particular moment for global AI governance: the EU AI Act enters its main enforcement phase in August 2026, governments worldwide are writing AI strategies, and the AI industry is searching for credible ethical frames. The encyclical's reception will be measured by how it is taken up in those debates, not only by how it is received within Catholic circles."
      - "@type": "Question"
        "name": "What does Magnifica Humanitas change?"
        "acceptedAnswer":
          "@type": "Answer"
          "text": "Encyclicals do not regulate. They establish moral frameworks that other actors then have to respond to. The Catholic Church does not write AI law, build AI products, or enforce AI standards. What an encyclical can do is provide a vocabulary, a framework, and a moral pressure point that shapes how the AI conversation unfolds over the next decade. Past encyclicals have shaped labor law (Rerum Novarum), peace negotiations (Pacem in Terris), and climate policy (Laudato Si). Magnifica Humanitas is positioned to do the same for AI."
